AGI - The take-off of the Starliner ship, > developed by Boeing, > which should bring NASA astronauts to the International Space Station >, was canceled about two hours before the scheduled time > due to a technical problem. An anomaly was detected in an Atlas V> rocket valve that should have pushed the capsule into orbit, announced the carrier manufacturer, the ULA group. "Nasa's priority is security," explained U.S. space agency leader Bill Nelson. The takeoff will be "when we are ready," he wrote on X.
&nbsp;
A new take-off attempt could theoretically take place in the day but for the moment no date has been announced. Other possibilities are Friday or Saturday days.&nbsp;Boeing bets a lot on this mission that should allow her to enter the narrow club of space vehicles that have transported humans to ISS. The American giant must prove that his vehicle is safe before he can start regular missions to the Space Station. All four years behind SpaceX>. The take-off of American astronauts Butch Wilmore and Suni> Williams was scheduled for 22:34, local time, from Cape Canaveral in Florida, when in Italy it was late night. At first the preparations had gone well: the astronauts had settled in their places, the rocket had been filled with fuel and the weather was ideal.
&nbsp;
Also for NASA, who ordered this vehicle ten years ago, the stakes are high: having a second vehicle in addition to that of SpaceX to transport American astronauts "is very important", said Dana Weigel, head of the ISS program. Weigel explained that this possibility would make it easier to respond to "different scenarios" in case of emergency, such as a problem with one of the spacecraft. The success of this mission is long awaited by Boeing who, in recent years, has faced several security problems of its aircraft.> But the same Starliner development program has turned into a saga marked by unpleasant surprises and setbacks.
&nbsp;
In 2019, during a first unmanned test, the capsule failed to position itself on the right trajectory and returned without reaching the Space Station. Then in 2021, just as the rocket was on the launch ramp to try again the flight, a problem of blocked valves forced the postponement. The empty ship finally managed to reach the ISS in May 2022. Boeing hoped to make the first flight with crew in the same year. But the problems discovered later, especially with the parachutes that brake the capsule when it comes to the atmosphere, have again created delays. "There were several surprises we had to overcome," said the manager of the Boeing Mark Nappi at the press conference. But "this has made our teams very strong," he assured. "It is quite typical that the development of a human spacecraft requires ten years," he added.&nbsp;

