AGI - Israel has struck the city of Rafah, in Gaza, during the night, trying to make "pressure" on Hamas in view of the talks that will be held today in Egypt with the aim of the approval of a proposal of truce that is considered satisfactory from both sides. After promising for weeks to push into the border city, on Monday Israel asked the Palestinians of the eastern part of Rafah to abandon what was called an "enlarged humanitarian zone" in view of a land raid. A correspondent of AFP reported heavy bombings that occurred all night while the Kuwaiti hospital, present in the city perimeter, declared at the early hours of Tuesday that five people had been killed and many other injuries in air attacks.
<h2> The yellow of the truce
After new and intense talks, Hamas declared that he had informed the mediators Egypt and Qatar of "approving their proposal for a ceasefire", pushing the crowd to get off in the square to Rafah. However, the Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office has judged the agreement as something still "far from Israel's essential demands," although the Tel Aviv government has announced that it wants to send negotiators to "come to an agreement". In the meantime, he added, "Israel continuing the operation to Rafah to exert a military pressure on Hamas in order to obtain the release of our hostages and the achievement of the other objectives of the war." The United States, close allies of Israel, declared to be "examined" the response of Hamas.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Khalil al-Hayya, a member of the most authoritative of Hamas, told Al Jazeera, a broadcaster based in Qatar and obscured in Israel, that the proposal agreed by Hamas provides a truce in three phases, and then specify how to include a complete withdrawal of Israel from Gaza, the return of displaced Palestinians due to the conflict and an exchange of hostage-prisoners, with the aim of a " ceased". Qatar has stated that in the morning it will send a delegation to Cairo to resume negotiations. Another Hamas official, speaking with AFP anonymously, said that Israel must now decide whether to accept or "obstruct" a truce.
<h2> The situation in Rafah</h2>
Renewing the appeal to leave Rafah, Israeli military spokesman Daniel Hagari stressed that the actions for now will not stop: "The planes have targeted more than 50 terrorist targets" throughout the city and over the last 24 hours. Meanwhile, the international alarm continues to be stronger on the possible consequences of an invasion of Israeli land in Rafah. An incursion in the city, located near the border with Egypt, would be "intolerable", said UN Secretary General Antonio Guterres, inviting Israel and Hamas "to take a step further" to reach an agreement. "It is an opportunity that cannot be lost and an invasion of land at Rafah would be intolerable for its devastating humanitarian consequences and its destabilizing impact on the region," Guterres added.
&nbsp;
The Egyptian Foreign Ministry, for its part, warned of "gravious humanitarian risks" for the more than a million inhabitants of Gaza who took refuge and urged Israel to "exercise maximum attention". Jordanian king Abdullah II asked US President Joe Biden to intervene to stop a "new massacre" at Rafah.> In a conversation with Netanyahu Monday, Biden reiterated "his clear position" contrary to an invasion of the city.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Netanyahu, however, pulls straight promising to send land troops to Rafah regardless of any truce and stating that it is necessary to eradicate the remaining forces of Hamas to prevent the bloody attacks of October 7 that unleashed the war in Gaza. According to the World Health Organization, about 1.2 million people are sheltered in Rafah. The Family Forum of Israeli hostages and dispersed families declared in a statement, after the announcement of Hamas of a possible truce, that "the time has come for all parties involved to respect their commitment and turn this into an agreement for the return of all hostages". Hamas said that Israel is planning a large-scale offensive "without taking into account the ongoing humanitarian catastrophe" in the Gaza Strip besieged > and the fate of the hostages held.
&nbsp;
Israel responded with an evacuation order from Rafah, "limited" and temporary, aimed at "bringing people out of danger" before direct actions. In the statement, the Tel Aviv army urged those who are in the eastern part of Rafah to head towards the "extended humanitarian zone" of Al-Mawasi, on the coast but humanitarian groups and associations said that Al-Mawasi is not ready to welcome such influx of people. The Palestinian authorities reported "migliaia" of tents that left the eastern part of the city slowly. When asked how many people should move, an Israeli military spokesperson replied: "The estimate is about 100,000 people" but, according to the Palestinian authorities, the designated evacuation zone already houses about 250,000 people, many of which are already eradicated from other places.
&nbsp;
Abdul Rahman Abu Jazar, 36 years old, told AFP that the area "does not have enough room for us even just to mount tents" because it is already full. "Where can we go?" he asked. The Unnicef warned that, precisely for this reason, about 600 thousand children in Rafah are likely to suffer "a further catastrophe". The main assistance group in Gaza, the <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-04-23/aiuti-entrano-a-gaza-unrwa-numero-piu-alto-26146801/">Unrwa</a>, added that an Israeli offensive to Rafah would mean "more suffering and dead among civilians". &nbsp;&nbsp;
