AGI - Parisians and residents of Ile de France's hinterland are fleeing from the French capital that from July will host the Paris Olympic Games 2024>, a maxi international sporting event that for them is not synonymous with celebration. To frighten them and to push them to desert the anticipated event are the chaos risk in public transport - especially in the metro, not air-conditioned - that will be stormed by the public, the increase in prices in bars, restaurants>, and in general in the commercial activities that come food.
Then there are those who, owner of one or more houses, decided to leave home momentarily to rent it on specialized sites, such as Airbnb, in order to obtain record gains. In particular, from July 26 to August 11, > the highlight of the Olympic Games, hotel prices, bed and breakfasts and apartments for rent > rose to the stars and the places available are gradually exhausting.
<div </div
&nbsp;
This desire to escape from Paris and the surrounding areas is reflected in several surveys relaunched by the Oltralpe media, although the results are contrasting according to the source. According to an Ipsos study for Trainline, almost one out of two living in the Paris region (47%) decided to leave the region in August > because of Paris 2024, in particular for the crowding of tourists and for the possible travel difficulties. A survey conducted by Harris Interactive for the Ministry of Tourism found instead that 69% of people living in the Paris region plans to stay in the region this summer, by choice or not.
<h2> Trade union appeal: "Don't go away"</h2>
So far, it does not seem to have aroused great effect the appeal launched by the socialist mayor of Paris, Anne Hidalgo, > who invited Parisians to stay in the capital to enjoy the Olympic Games. "We'll be together. Paris will be magnificent! Don't go away this summer, don't go away, it would be a bullshit, it'll be amazing," Hidalgo said with tones on last February. The announcement of the Ile de France region, according to which several transport lines will be increased up to 70% during the Olympics and Paralympics period. >
<div </div
&nbsp;
On the other hand, some metro stops will be closed for security reasons, complicating not little the movements of those who will work during that period. In addition, the residents of the French capital are restrictions on the circulation imposed in certain areas > which will be venues for competitions and reception infrastructures of athletes. stringent rules that remind many of the infamous Covid period, thus representing an additional reason for escape from Paris.
And then, for those who are accustomed to cycling, also using the popular 'Vèlib' service, the closure of entire neighborhoods will make impossible the storage of rental bikes.> To play against a strong participation of the population in the Olympics, it was also the cost of selling - in some cases prohibitive - tickets to attend some competitions. However, the fact that Paris is assaulted by tourists and Olympic participants will have repercussions on the workers, in many cases forced holidays if their company does not grant telework.
<div </div
&nbsp;
Meanwhile the railway sites 'Sncf' are stormed by those looking for a low cost ticket > to escape from the capital already from mid-July, which coincides then with the period of closure of the schools and summer holiday of Paris, but not only. However, the escape of residents for the Olympics is a well-established demographic trend: the population of the French capital is reduced from year to year. According to the data of the Insee (National Statistical Institute) released last December, 12,795 Paris left the capital within a year, > between 2020 and 2021. In all, 73.377 people made this choice between 2015 and 2021, because of the rents too expensive, public transport not always optimal, moved by the desire to approach nature, also thanks to the flexibility of telework.&nbsp;
